<h1>
Minnesota reaches settlement with pharmaceutical company over âpay-for-delayâ behavior
</h1>
	<p class="lede">Endo settles with 18 states over charges it protected its monopoly on Lidoderm through illegal, anti-competitive conduct </p>
	
	
	<p><strong>July 25, 2019 (SAINT PAUL)</strong> â Attorney General Keith  Ellison announced today that Minnesota and 17 other states have reached an  agreement with Endo International plc and Endo Pharmaceuticals Inc. over anti-competitive, &ldquo;pay-for-delay&rdquo; conduct  related to Endo&rsquo;s sale of Lidoderm, a pain-relief drug that treats  complications from shingles.</p>
    <p>&ldquo;One of the  reasons the cost of pharmaceutical drugs is so high is illegal behavior by drug  companies,&rdquo; Attorney General Ellison said. &ldquo;Endo tried to get away with a  &lsquo;pay-for-delay&rsquo; scheme that stifled competition, forced consumers to pay  inflated prices for a much-needed drug, and made it harder for people to afford  their lives. We held them accountable for it. </p>
    <p>&ldquo;With this  settlement, we&rsquo;re sending a message to any drug company even thinking about  &lsquo;pay-for-delay&rsquo; or other illegal conduct that we&rsquo;ll hold them accountable,  too,&rdquo; Attorney General Ellison added.</p>
    <p>The states accused Endo of  illegal, anti-competitive conduct due to its participation in a &ldquo;pay-for-delay&rdquo;  agreement to protect a monopoly on Lidoderm, for  which it was the branded distributor and patent-holder. (Lidoderm is the  brand-name for lidocaine patches, a transdermal patch widely prescribed for  relief of pain associated with post-herpetic neuralgia, a common complication  of shingles.) Endo and Teikoku, the branded manufacturer of Lidoderm, sued  Watson, a potential generic competitor, for patent infringement in order to  prevent Watson&rsquo;s FDA-approved launch of its generic version of the drug in  August 2012.&nbsp;Despite the fact that Endo was the plaintiff, the suit  settled with Endo agreeing to provide Watson a payment in the form of product  for Watson to sell that had a value of $96â240 million. It also included an  agreement that Endo would not launch its own authorized generic to compete with  Watson&rsquo;s eventual generic.&nbsp;In exchange, Watson delayed entering the market  with its generic lidocaine patches until September 2013.&nbsp; This kind of  conduct is called a &ldquo;reverse settlement&rdquo; or &ldquo;pay-for-delay.&rdquo; </p>
    <p>At the time  of the &ldquo;pay-for-delay&rdquo; agreement, Lidoderm was Endo&rsquo;s most important branded  prescription-drug product. In 2011, Endo generated more than $825 million from  its branded Lidoderm patches, comprising 30% of Endo&rsquo;s total annual revenues. </p>
    <p>The agreement is focused on  injunctive relief and preventing future conduct. The injunction prohibits Endo  from paying or incentivizing a generic drug maker to delay entry into the drug  market or to delay researching, developing, manufacturing, marketing or selling  any drug product. Endo will also pay the states a total of $2.3 million, which  the states will use to enforce the injunctive terms and to stop other  anti-competitive conduct in the pharmaceutical industry.</p>
    <p>Endo Pharmaceuticals Inc. is a  for-profit Delaware corporation that markets and sells Lidoderm and other drugs  throughout the United States.<strong> </strong>Endo International plc is the parent  company to Endo Pharmaceuticals Inc. with global headquarters in Ireland and  U.S. headquarters in Pennsylvania.&nbsp; <strong></strong></p>
